  "slug": "pork-and-apple-casserole",
  "title": "Pork and Apple Casserole",
  "subtitle": "Braised pork shoulder with Bramley apple and dry cider in a cream-finished sauce",
  "excerpt": "Pork shoulder braised with dry cider, Bramley apple, and sage produces a casserole that is rich, gently sweet, and deeply savoury. The apple dissolves into the sauce during cooking; the cream finishes it. This is a 2-hour dish with 20 minutes of active work.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: pork stewed with apple. Traditional West Country British cooking with cider. Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): pork with apple and cider.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pork shoulder is the right cut here: fatty enough to stay moist through 2 hours of braising and flavourful enough to hold its own against the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "dry cider",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr58d70000jwv40ea2doef"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " and apple. A leaner cut such as loin will dry out long before the braise is finished.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Bramley apple",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr58dw0001jwv4ulq4fsul"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " needs no peeling or precise preparation: rough chunks added to the pot will dissolve entirely during the braise. The result is a sauce with apple woven through it rather than apple pieces in a sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
