      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown and braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a large casserole over high heat. Season the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{pork-shoulder}} of pork shoulder",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and dust with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Brown in batches until golden on all sides. Remove and set aside. Reduce heat to medium. Add the onion and cook for 5 minutes. Add garlic and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sage}} of sage leaves",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Return the pork. Pour in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{cider-dry}} of dry cider",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and let it bubble for 2 minutes. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and the apple. Bring to a simmer. Cover and cook in a 160°C oven (or on the lowest hob heat) for 90-100 minutes until the pork is completely tender.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finish the sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the pork and keep warm. If the sauce is thin, simmer uncovered for 10 minutes to reduce. Stir in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{double-cream}} of cream",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and the Dijon mustard if using. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Return the pork to the sauce and serve.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Add a splash of cider vinegar or lemon juice to cut the sweetness. Next time use a fully dry cider and Bramley only.",
              "cause": "Sweet cider used instead of dry, or Bramley was substituted with eating apples",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too sweet"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pork shoulder has enough fat to stay moist. Ensure the oven is no higher than 160°C and the pot is covered.",
              "cause": "Lean cut used, or cooked at too high a temperature",
              "symptom": "Pork is dry and stringy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add the apple at the start of the braise and cut it into small chunks so it dissolves fully.",
              "cause": "Added too late in cooking, or cut too large",
              "symptom": "Apple pieces are still intact"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Allow the sauce to drop below a boil before adding cream. Once cream is in, do not let the sauce boil hard again.",
              "cause": "Sauce was boiling when the cream went in",
              "symptom": "Cream splits when added"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pork and apple is one of the oldest pairing in British cooking. The combination appears in medieval cookery manuscripts and remains a constant across the centuries. The cider version is associated with the West Country, where both pigs and apple orchards have been central to the farming economy for centuries. Served with mashed potato or a plain boiled grain, it is one of the most satisfying autumn and winter suppers in the British repertoire.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
